## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort to Cooperative Cancellation

### Pattern Classification: **Timeout Enforcement**

The code aborts a thread that exceeds a time limit. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Problems in the Original Code

| API | .NET 8 Behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw; // caller cancelled — propagate, don't wrap
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Cancellation is cooperative** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the token won't interrupt a CPU-bound `Func<T>` that never checks it. If `work` is a tight loop, it must call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` ≠ killing the work** | When the timeout fires, `WaitAsync` throws immediately but `work` keeps running on the thread pool. The work becomes fire-and-forget. This matches the old behavior (aborted threads didn't guarantee instant cleanup either). |
| **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaking a `CTS` with `CancelAfter` leaks an internal timer. Always `using`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary to convert to `TimeoutException`. |

### If `work` Must Actually Stop

For the cancellation to be effective, refactor `work` to accept a `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                   .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                   .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Then the work cooperates:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### If Work Is Truly Uncooperative (e.g., native call)

Move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` — this is the only way to forcibly terminate uncooperative code in modern .NET. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort`.
